<methodology slug="market-research-tam-sam-som">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>research</group>
    <domain>market-researcher</domain>
    <summary>Quantifies market opportunity through three nested estimates using top-down, bottom-up, and competitor-based methods. Always triangulate; flag divergence >2x.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>market-sizing</tag>
      <tag>tam-sam-som</tag>
      <tag>market-research</tag>
      <tag>investor-pitch</tag>
      <tag>gating</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Market Research — TAM/SAM/SOM</title>
    <summary>TAM/SAM/SOM sizing quantifies market opportunity through three nested estimates using top-down, bottom-up, and competitor-based methods. The core rule: always triangulate with both top-down and bottom-up; if the two diverge more than 2x, flag it as a research gap rather than averaging the numbers. The market-researcher lens produces three audience-specific cuts from the same canonical base: an investor cut, a GTM cut, and a pricing cut.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Entrepreneurs either overestimate markets (citing billion-dollar TAMs with no grounding) or underestimate them (ignoring the bottom-up path to $1M ARR). Investor partners spot the gap between the slide number and the financial model in 90 seconds. GTM channel budgets that lack per-channel SAM ceilings routinely double-count customers. A rigorous three-cut methodology forces each view to derive from the same canonical base and flags the moment they diverge.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Seed/Series-A pitch deck market slide needs three numbers, three sources, one chart</item>
        <item>GTM segmentation kickoff: SAM split per channel so the marketer can allocate CAC budget</item>
        <item>Pricing-tier sizing: each tier needs its own ARPU × addressable-count math</item>
        <item>Re-sizing after a pivot, geography expansion, or new pricing page</item>
        <item>Board update comparing SOM-actual vs. SOM-plan for the trailing quarter</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Hobby projects, internal tooling, free OSS — investor audience absent, sizing is theatre</item>
        <item>Two-sided marketplaces pre-launch — supply liquidity dominates raw market size</item>
        <item>Replacement for win/loss interviews — TAM/SAM/SOM does not explain why deals close</item>
        <item>Already-shipping products where bottom-up cohort revenue forecasts are stronger</item>
        <item>Solo freemium-with-no-paid-plan — SAM × ARPU collapses to zero</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Definitions">
      <list>
        <item>TAM (Total Addressable Market): total revenue if you captured 100% of potential buyers — formula: total potential customers × average revenue per customer per year</item>
        <item>SAM (Serviceable Available Market): portion of TAM actually reachable given geography, language, industry, company size, and tech constraints — formula: TAM × segment percentage</item>
        <item>SOM (Serviceable Obtainable Market): realistic market share in 3-5 years — formula: SAM × realistic market share percentage (Year 1: 0.1-0.5%, Year 3: 1-3%, Year 5: 3-10%)</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Method 1 — Top-Down">
      <p>Start with an industry report, narrow down through segmentation filters (geography, industry, company size, tech stack). Use case: shows opportunity ceiling; establishes TAM for investor communication.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Cite source, publication year, and page number for every top-down number. Reject any row with a dollar figure but no URL.</statement>
        <rationale>Top-down numbers from Gartner/Statista are routinely inflated 3-10x. LLMs confidently parrot fabricated CAGRs with two decimal places. Citation discipline is the only defense.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Method 2 — Bottom-Up">
      <p>Start from countable potential customers, multiply by conversion rate and price. Use case: grounds the SOM in operational reality; more credible to investors than top-down alone.</p>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[15M freelancers in target geography
× 0.5% reachable with current marketing budget
= 75,000 addressable prospects
× 1% Year 1 trial conversion
= 750 customers
× $20/mo × 12
= $180K Year 1 SOM]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Method 3 — Competitor-Based">
      <p>Estimate total market from visible competitor revenues, then derive realistic share. Use case: cross-check for top-down and bottom-up; anchors SOM to actual market capacity.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Find competitor ARR estimates: Crunchbase funding data, SimilarWeb traffic × revenue per visit, LinkedIn employee count × $200K revenue per employee rule of thumb, or pricing × estimated customer count</item>
        <item>Sum visible competitor revenues to estimate total market</item>
        <item>Apply realistic share (1% of $500M market = $5M SOM at Year 3)</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Validation Checks">
      <rule>
        <statement>Always triangulate with both top-down and bottom-up. If the two results diverge more than 2x, flag it as a research gap — do not average the numbers or pick the more favorable one.</statement>
        <rationale>Divergence above 2x signals a definitional mismatch, a data quality problem, or an unconsidered constraint. Averaging hides the problem; flagging it forces investigation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Does the TAM feel real? Compare against public market research data</item>
        <item>Is the SAM specific enough? Can you name 100 target customers right now?</item>
        <item>Is the SOM achievable? Can you explain the operational path to get there?</item>
        <item>Does bottom-up match top-down within 2x? If not, document the gap</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Investor Cut">
      <list>
        <item>One slide, three numbers (TAM / SAM / SOM), three sources, one chart, 40 words maximum</item>
        <item>TAM labeled explicitly as "if-100% scenario" in a footnote — partners reward honesty</item>
        <item>SOM growth arrow must match the Y5 ARR in the financial model exactly</item>
        <item>Include 2 public-comp equivalents at the same stage for instant credibility</item>
        <item>Round aggressively for the slide ($8B), preserve precision in the appendix ($8.27B) — never reverse</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>The investor cut must fit on one slide. If it does not, the agent has not finished the work.</statement>
        <rationale>An overloaded market slide signals that the founder cannot explain the opportunity succinctly. Partners use this as a signal about pitch clarity.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="GTM Cut">
      <list>
        <item>Split SAM into mutually exclusive acquisition channels: PLG (low CAC, low ACV), outbound (high CAC, high ACV), partner (medium), content/SEO (decaying low CAC)</item>
        <item>Each bucket has a SAM ceiling — total reachable accounts via that channel only</item>
        <item>CAC envelope per bucket comes from pricing-research.md; any tier where bucket-CAC exceeds 0.33 × tier-LTV is GTM-blocked</item>
        <item>Geography splits must align with the pricing cut — no GTM motion in regions without localized pricing</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>GTM channel buckets must be mutually exclusive. Double-counting a customer between PLG and outbound is the most common GTM-cut audit failure.</statement>
        <rationale>Overlapping channel buckets inflate the reachable market and produce GTM plans that exceed the actual addressable population.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Pricing-Tier Cut">
      <list>
        <item>For each pricing tier: tier-SAM = SAM × tier-mix percentage, tier-SOM = tier-SAM × realistic-share-for-tier</item>
        <item>Tier-mix reality: most SaaS land 60-70% Starter, 25-30% Pro, 5-10% Enterprise — a deck claiming 40% Enterprise requires evidence</item>
        <item>LTV uses tier-specific churn, not blended rate — Starter churn is often 3-5x Enterprise churn</item>
        <item>Any tier whose Y3 SOM is below 6 months of one engineer's salary should be cut from the deck — distraction</item>
        <item>Express tier-SOM in customer count first ("12,000 Pro seats"), dollars second — investors trust counts more</item>
      </list>
      <reference path="templates/tier-som.sh">Script decomposing SAM/SOM per tier with LTV/CAC sanity check</reference>
    </section>
    <section name="Common Mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Presenting only TAM without a bottom-up SOM calculation</description>
        <reason>TAM is the ceiling; SOM is what determines whether the business is worth building. Investors require both; a TAM-only deck signals the founder has not done the work.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Trusting a single industry report source</description>
        <reason>Single-source TAMs are the number-one reason investor memos fall apart. Triangulate from at least 3 independent sources and publish the range, not a point estimate.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Ignoring competitor share in the SOM calculation</description>
        <reason>SOM without subtracting established competitor share overestimates the realistically capturable market in a competitive category.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Static SOM in a fast-moving category</description>
        <reason>SOM must be redrawn every 6 months in high-CAGR categories; a stale curve presented as current breaks credibility in investor Q&amp;A.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="AI-Agent Gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent conflates TAM (gross addressable revenue) with ARR projection (net revenue)</description>
        <reason>Both numbers must appear with explicit labels every time; they are not interchangeable and differ by assumptions about market share, pricing, and churn.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Tier-mix defaulting to even splits (33/33/33 across Starter/Pro/Enterprise)</description>
        <reason>Even splits never match reality; force the agent to read category benchmarks (OpenView, ChartMogul) before assigning tier-mix percentages.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent puts the same customer account in both PLG and outbound channel buckets</description>
        <reason>Each customer appears in exactly one channel bucket; require a uniqueness key per row in the GTM cut model.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent generates 200 words for the investor slide</description>
        <reason>Investor cut is capped at 40 words on the slide; all additional detail goes in the appendix where partners can read it if challenged.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent cites a hallucinated comparable ("Stripe is at 12% of TAM") without a source URL</description>
        <reason>Require a URL for every comparable cited on the investor cut; strike any row without one.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent uses headline list price as tier ARPU rather than effective ARPU</description>
        <reason>Effective ARPU = list × (1 - discount) × annual-billing-mix; require an explicit effective-ARPU column, not list price.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/market-sizing-report.md" purpose="Full market sizing report with TAM/SAM/SOM calculations, bottom-up funnel, and validation table"/>
      <template path="templates/quick-market-check.md" purpose="15-minute rough market check for early-stage screening"/>
      <template path="templates/tier-som.sh" purpose="Bash script that decomposes SAM/SOM per pricing tier with LTV/CAC sanity check from a CSV of tier data"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
